post_text: The U.S. government uses data collected from the Census to determine the amount of funding our schools receive. East Valley Schools receive approximately 7% of our annual revenue from these federal sources so it is extremely important that we capture an accurate representation of our community during this 2020 Census. Time is running, but you can still self respond until September 30th. Click on the link to make sure your family is part of the count! https://2020census.gov/en.html?utm_campaign=20200914msprts1ccpuprs&utm_content=&utm_medium=email&utm_source=govdelivery#Census2020

post_text:
Following Governor Inslee’s press conference yesterday, the Yakima Health District made their official recommendations for a virtual start for schools in Yakima County. Given the guidelines outlined by the Washington State Department of Health and this strong recommendation from our local health authorities, we would like to confirm that our East Valley Schools will begin 100% virtual with an enhanced distance learning model on Tuesday, September 8, 2020, as indicated in our released communication earlier this week. Visit our website to read this full communication. www.evsd90.org

More details on this virtual start to our 2020-2021 school year will be coming within the next couple of weeks.

A month ago, Yakima had one of the highest COVID-19 rates in the country. Today, they have bent the curve and are one of the few counties in WA heading in the right direction.

They went from 65% to 95% of people wearing masks.

Congratulations to EVHS student, Michael McDowell, who recently enlisted in the Army after 3 successful years in our EVHS JROTC program! Being in the JROTC opens doors for students who are considering a career in the military including...
🇺🇸 Enlisting with E3 status instead of E1 (with 3 years of JROTC service) which includes an enhanced beginning salary

🇺🇸 Under the new Core 24, JROTC course credits can be substituted for other courses like foreign language and more.

🇺🇸 Experience prepares students for the rigor of the ASVAB, the work force and more.

#EVdoesCTE For more information, visit https://eastvalleyhigh.evsd90.org/apps/pages/JROTC

post_text:
🖐🏻🖐🏽 Raise your hand in the comments below if your house is part of the count!! 🖐🏼🖐🏾Yesterday Washington State hit a huge milestone in the 2020 Census with 67.2% of households responding! This means we have the highest response rate this side of the Rocky Mountains! Even as we celebrate, we still have work to do. Make sure EVERYONE living in your house (even those that aren't relatives) are part of the count. Information from the Census helps provide essential funding for our schools and hospitals! It is so easy for people to self-respond now:

Online at www.2020census.gov
Call toll-free 844.330.2020 (English) or 844.469.2020 (Spanish) from 4 .am. to 11 p.m.
Return paper form (if you received one) #EastValleyEngaged #2020census

Yakima Health District
June 1 at 10:16 AM ·

Starting June 3rd, Yakima County residents are directed to wear face coverings in indoor and outdoor public settings when they can’t keep 6 feet apart from people they don’t live with. This is to protect others and slow the spread of COVID-19 in our community. Read more on the health officer's directive on our website: https://www.yakimacounty.us/2412/Mask-Directive-Summary #COVID19YKM #YakimaTogether

Learn how to make your own face mask at: https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/prevent-getting-sick/how-to-make-cloth-face-covering.html

post_text:
Just moments ago, Moxee Elementary called an emergency virtual staff meeting for a very exciting reason.... to announce our first ever Classified Crystal Hop winner! Congratulations to our 2020 Classified Employee of the Year, Mary Frank!

Mary has been a dedicated member of our Moxee Elementary team, serving our students as a paraprofessional since 2015. Mary supports some of our most struggling students daily by building up their self-confidence with her reassurance and love. She is known for her welcoming presence and kind-hearted spirit. Nominator, Beth Caton, says of Mary, "She lets students know they can learn... Students don't give up on themselves because they know they have a teacher who believes in them."

Mary Frank, thank you for all you do to positively impact the lives of our East Valley kids!

post_text:
Earlier this afternoon, in a Google Meet with 70+ community members and fellow educators of EVHS, we were able to recognize Mr. Michael Duerre as our first Crystal Hop Educator of the Year!

Among many notable accomplishments, Mr. Duerre is known for his dedication to serving our students at EVHS through his leadership role as the ASB advisor and for serving his peers as the East Valley Education Association President. He is a master at creating connections with kids that positively impact their lives and futures. Thanks for being a role model for our EV students and for devoting yourself so willingly to the betterment of our East Valley community. Congratulations Mr. Duerre!!

shared_text:
East Valley Red Devils
May 4 at 10:10 AM ·

Hey, Red Devils! Would you like to get involved with ASB and help improve our school culture? Then YOU should consider running for a position as a Class Officer! The positions are President, Vice President, Secretary, Treasurer, and Activities Coordinator. As a Class Officer, you will be a part of the ASB Council and will have the opportunity to make a positive change in our school and help plan activities and events. If you are interested, please fill out the Petition to Run for Elected Office in Google Drive. You will need to open the document, make a copy of your own (go to File, pull down to “make a copy” and save it on your own drive), and then share it with Mr. Duerre, EVHS ASB Advisor, when you have filled it out. If you have questions, please contact Mr. Duerre at duerre.michael@evsd90.org. Petitions are due by MONDAY, MAY 11.

Please see link below:

https://docs.google.com/document/d/1MBSoFCXwkdS8xxrXP9WjEvRt23k1DBMcj785Ry8ofGg/edit?usp=sharing

post_text:
We are offering free meals for all children ages 1-18, regardless of family income. To reduce the risk of exposure to COVID-19 through person to person contact, as well as transportation burdens on families, we are now operating bulk meal distributions. Bulk meals consist of 5 breakfasts and 5 lunches for each child. These bulk meal distributions will be offered as a “Grab and Go” service from Terrace Heights Elementary and Moxee Elementary on Tuesdays, from 11:00 a.m. to 12:30 p.m. Children must be present to receive meals.

If you do not have transportation to pick-up meals for your child(ren), please contact our Food Services Department at (509) 573-7435

post_text:
Earlier this morning, the Yakima Health District issued a stay at home order, with the exception of essential services, for Yakima County. The safety of our students, staff and community is our highest priority. We will continue to offer meals for our East Valley kids that are in need. However, in an effort to limit the number of contacts our staff make each day and, to reduce the impact of COVID-19 in our community, we will be reducing the number of Grab n’ Go stations we will offer. Beginning tomorrow, Tuesday, March 24th, we will only be serving meals at Terrace Heights Elementary and Moxee Elementary.

We understand that this closure is causing hardships and inconveniences for many of our families. We are doing our best to support our community during this time, by ensuring the safety of our staff, students and family members.

Thank you for your patience and understanding as we work through this rapidly evolving situation.

post_text:
Student safety is our highest priority. Earlier this morning, the Yakima Health District issued a stay at home order, with the exception of essential services, for Yakima County, to limit the impact of COVID-19 in our community. At this time, we plan to discontinue the use of playground equipment and sport courts on our campuses, as they are not essential services.

While we understand the desire to get outside with kids to enjoy this nice spring weather, we are also noticing large groups of children and adults congregating on our campuses around playgrounds and sports courts. Children meeting outside, in larger groups, are at higher risk for contracting COVID-19. The Centers for Disease Control indicates that the novel coronavirus can live for up to 72 hours on plastic surfaces.

We understand that this closure is causing hardships and inconveniences for many of our families. We are doing our best to support our community during this time, by ensuring the safety of our staff, students and family members.

Thank you for your patience and understanding.

🍎Terrace Heights Elementary
🍎Moxee Elementary
🍎East Valley Central Middle School

A lunch for the current day and a breakfast for the following day will be provided at each location between 11:00 am and 12:30 pm (Monday through Friday). Children must be present to receive a meal.

post_text:
The amount of funding our schools get is impacted by the results of the U.S. Census.

Washington schools received more than a billion dollars of federal funding in 2017, including more than $230 million for special education and $257 million for child nutrition programs. Last year East Valley schools received $2,828,572 in federal funding.

The Census only happens once every 10 years, and it’s right around the corner! Watch your mailbox for information from the U.S. Census Bureau with directions on how to fill out the census. It’s quick, it’s easy, and it helps ensure that our schools get the support they deserve.

Every 10 years, the U.S. Constitution requires a count of everyone living in the country. The info gathered in the Census helps determine how much federal funding goes to our communities to support important services like roads, hospitals and SCHOOLS!! It also determines the number of representatives Washington will have in Congress. Make sure you're part of the count this spring!

Check out 2020census.gov to learn more.

post_text:
Who does CTE benefit? The answer is everyone!

* CTE Works for High School Students- Students involved in CTE are more engaged, graduate at higher rates and typically go on to postsecondary education.
* CTE Works for Business- CTE addresses the needs of industries and helps close the skills gap.
* CTE Works for College Students and Adults- Postsecondary CTE prepares students and adults for in-demand careers, and allows them to take on less debt.
* CTE Works for the Economy- Investing in CTE yields big returns for state economies.

#EVdoesCTE #CTEmonth #CareerTechEd #FutureBound

post_text:
Food Safety Alert - CDC, public health and regulatory officials in several states, and the U.S. Food and Drug Administration (FDA) are investigating a multistate outbreak of E.coli infections linked to romaine lettuce harvested from the Salinas, California growing region. CDC is advising that consumers not eat any romaine lettuce harvested from the Salinas, CA growing region.

While we do not serve romaine lettuce in East Valley, we do serve other varieties of lettuce grown in this region. As a precautionary measure, we have disposed of all lettuce and will not be serving any until after Thanksgiving break. When we return next week we will resume serving our students lettuce grown from another region not linked to this outbreak.

https://www.cdc.gov/ecoli/2019/o157h7-11-19/index.html CDC LinK

post_text:
Update: Wednesday, October 16, 2019 - Late yesterday afternoon a section of concrete shifted on the southeast side of our existing East Valley High School building. This is the side that is currently exposed due to demolition for the eventual rebuild of our high school. Please note that this section of the building is a significant distance from the classrooms that are currently being used to house our students and staff.

As a result of this shift, we issued a precautionary school closure for the day to ensure the safety of our students and staff while contractors, engineers and architects, further evaluate the site. As we learn more throughout the day, we will provide an update for our East Valley community.
text:
Update: Wednesday, October 16, 2019 - Late yesterday afternoon a section of concrete shifted on the southeast side of our existing East Valley High School building. This is the side that is currently exposed due to demolition for the eventual rebuild of our high school. Please note that this section of the building is a significant distance from the classrooms that are currently being used to house our students and staff.

As a result of this shift, we issued a precautionary school closure for the day to ensure the safety of our students and staff while contractors, engineers and architects, further evaluate the site. As we learn more throughout the day, we will provide an update for our East Valley community.

post_text:
Due to unforeseen circumstances related to our construction project, East Valley High School will be closed tomorrow, Wednesday, October 16, 2019, for the entire school day. All other schools in the district will operate on their normal schedules. All after school athletic activities will operate as planned. The main office in the new building will be open for business from 7:30 a.m. – 3:45 p.m. It will be a regular work day for all EVHS staff. EVHS staff should report to the main office in the new building.

Students scheduled to take the PSAT:
Please report to the new building by 7:50 a.m. The test will take place at the fire station as previously planned. Students who require transportation for the PSAT will ride the bus as usual. After the test is over, students are free to leave. If students need transportation home, it will be provided at the regular time. Students that remain, will be able to receive lunch and work in the new building for the remainder of the day.

post_text:
Attention Red Devils! We are excited to welcome our high school students back to campus next week. To make accommodations for our construction project, we will need to delay the start of the 2019-2020 school year until Wednesday, September 4, 2019. (All other East Valley Schools will begin as scheduled on Tuesday, September 3rd. )

When students arrive on Wednesday, they will need to report to Earl Barden Stadium by 7:50 a.m. to pick-up their schedules. From 7:50 a.m. to 9:50 a.m. students will meet with their advisory teachers to review school maps and tour the campus. Breakfast will be available in the auxiliary gym from 7:20 a.m. to 7:50 a.m..

Later this week we will post maps showing our designated student pathways and classroom numbers online at eastvalleyhigh.evsd90.org. If you have any additional questions, please contact our main office at 573-7400.
